Date:12/17/2011 12:51:59 AM
From:E_K_S
IDSA ( http://www.isa-inc.com/ )

I was thinking the same thing on the price lag/decline. The larger players
hedge their inventory but these folks are too small and are vulnerable to the
commodity price swings from when they buy and sell their scrap inventory.
Therefore, do you buy this one based on the value of their inventory in process
and the current (or future) price of the commodity?

So maybe BV is the starting point. Then you calculate the value of their "in
process" inventory. If their inventory turns over every 10 days then they
either lose or gain based on the price paid vs the price sold at the beginning
and ending inventory turn. The simple buy decision would be to see where the
alloy prices are trending over the last 30 days. If commodity prices are
falling, their "in process" inventory margins will be small. If commodity
prices are rising, their "in process" inventory margins should be large.

They only operate four separate recycling centers so every inventory turn is
important. They probably have different inventory turns for each commodity they
recycle too.

IDSA is thinly traded so you are probably correct to set a low ball "value"
entry point (below $5.00/share) and then sell at the 200 day MA price and/or as
commodity prices trend higher. It does not appear they are expanding as I did
not see any mention of adding new recycle centers any time soon.

EKS
